✅ PART 1(a): Create & Attach EBS Volume to EC2
🔹 Step 1: Create EBS Volume

Go to:

AWS Console → EC2 → Volumes → Create Volume

Choose:

Volume type: gp3 (recommended)

Size: 10–20 GB (example)

Availability Zone: ⚠ Must be SAME as EC2 instance

Click Create Volume

🔹 Step 2: Attach Volume to EC2

Select newly created volume

Click Actions → Attach Volume

Choose your EC2 instance

Device name: /dev/xvdf

Click Attach

⚠ Important: Volume & EC2 must be in same AZ.

🔹 Step 3: Verify in Linux

SSH into instance:

lsblk

You will see something like:

nvme0n1   (root disk)
nvme1n1   (new EBS volume)
✅ PART 1(b): Scale EC2 (Increase CPU & RAM)

This changes instance type.

🔹 Step 1: Stop Instance

EC2 → Instances
Select instance → Instance State → Stop

⚠ You cannot change type while running.

🔹 Step 2: Change Instance Type

Click:

Actions → Instance Settings → Change Instance Type

Example:

From: t2.micro

To: t2.medium (more CPU + RAM)

Click Apply

🔹 Step 3: Start Instance

Click:

Instance State → Start

✅ Instance now has increased CPU & RAM.

✅ PART 2: Permanently Mount EBS Volume (Data Persistence)

Now we make sure volume mounts automatically after reboot.

🔹 Step 1: Check Disk
lsblk

New disk usually appears as:

/dev/nvme1n1
🔹 Step 2: Create Partition
sudo fdisk /dev/nvme1n1

Inside fdisk:

n
p
Enter
Enter
Enter
w

Then:

sudo partprobe

Now check:

lsblk

You should see:

nvme1n1p1
🔹 Step 3: Format Partition
sudo mkfs.xfs /dev/nvme1n1p1
🔹 Step 4: Create Mount Directory
sudo mkdir /mnt/archana
🔹 Step 5: Mount Volume
sudo mount /dev/nvme1n1p1 /mnt/archana

Verify:

df -h
🔹 Step 6: Make It Permanent (VERY IMPORTANT)

Get UUID:

sudo blkid

Example:

UUID="f1e294e6-7657-4761-bba5-bb2d0eab3936"

Edit fstab:

sudo nano /etc/fstab

Add:

UUID=f1e294e6-7657-4761-bba5-bb2d0eab3936 /mnt/archana xfs defaults,nofail 0 0

Save & exit.

Test:

sudo mount -a
🔹 Step 7: Test Persistence
sudo reboot

After reconnect:

df -h

If mounted → ✅ Successful if not then
sudo mount /dev/nvme1n1p1 /mnt/archana
df -h

✅ PART 3: Snapshot & Cross-Region Volume
🔹 Step 1: Create Snapshot

EC2 → Volumes
Select volume → Actions → Create Snapshot

Add name → Click Create

🔹 Step 2: Copy Snapshot to Another Region

EC2 → Snapshots
Select snapshot → Actions → Copy Snapshot

Choose destination region
Click Copy

Wait until status = Completed

🔹 Step 3: Switch Region

Top-right corner → Change region to destination.

🔹 Step 4: Create Volume From Snapshot

EC2 → Snapshots
Select copied snapshot → Create Volume

Choose:

AZ (must match target EC2)

Volume type

Size

Click Create

🔹 Step 5: Attach to EC2 in New Region

EC2 → Volumes
Select new volume → Attach Volume
Choose instance → Attach

🔹 Step 6: Mount It in Linux

On new instance:

lsblk

Then:

sudo mkdir /mnt/archana
sudo mount /dev/nvme1n1p1 /mnt/archana

✅ All previous data will be there.
